    {
      "id": "4c6276f5b798dee7dde82a3229908787a0e0595b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-14 01:02:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nJohn, it definitely seems like a number of those stats are of very minimal use. They weren't in the 1.8 stats. Is it possible we remove these counters selectively?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "296d023881df8a3be45c6cdd3ff4b18c9e50eba0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-14 01:34:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> John, it definitely seems like a number of those stats are of very minimal use. They weren't in the 1.8 stats. Is it possible we remove these counters selectively?\n\nYes we can. I've been thinking about this and I think the best thing may be to move the interesting operations to the front of struct md_ops and the boring ones to the back. Then define NUM_MD_OPS appropriately and modify EXP_MD_COUNTER_INCREMENT() to only tally if the offset is less than NUM_MD_OPS.\n\nAlternatively we could just prune invocations of EXP_MD_COUNTER_INCREMENT() from the md_ops wrappers corresponding to boring operations.\n\nI'm open to suggestions on this, as well as on the issue of which counters to remove.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "e8b74f726bac87eec140592aab1068ce9beaba63",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-05-14 02:57:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.4/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/47264652-bc40-11e2-96d6-52540035b04c).  Ran 14 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "1885eb8570dca99507fd8ed330895e9411ab6a48",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-14 04:50:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nI think it makes sense to do both. Moving the main methods to the start will reduce memory usage, and removing the unused calls will avoid extra branches from the code.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "5bfd94d9527842d2773d3b86cf860231a0937db7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-17 16:17:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> I think it makes sense to do both. Moving the main methods to the start will reduce memory usage, and removing the unused calls will avoid extra branches from the code.\n\nI defined MD_STATS_FIRST_OP to be m_close and MD_STATS_LAST_OP to be m_revalidate_lock and rearranged the methods in md_ops so that the \"interesting\" counters would be these two and all in between. I adjusted EXP_MD_COUNTER_INCREMENT() to only tally ops in this range but did not change any of the wrappers since the condition to tally was a compile time constant. I disassembled a few files that called md_ops wrappers and verified that the \"boring\" functions did not contain a call to lprocfs_stats_incr() from EXP_MD_COUNTER_INCREMENT().\n\nLet me know if you think I should remove the EXP_MD_COUNTER_INCREMENT() invocations from the boring functions.\n\nHere are the interesting functions:\n\n+ m_close\n+ m_create\n+ m_done_writing\n+ m_enqueue\n+ m_getattr\n+ m_getattr_name\n+ m_intent_lock\n+ m_link\n+ m_rename\n+ m_setattr\n+ m_fsync - renamed from m_sync\n+ m_readpage\n+ m_unlink\n+ m_setxattr\n+ m_getxattr\n+ m_intent_getattr_async\n+ m_revalidate_lock\n\nHere are the boring ones:\n\n- m_is_subdir - Not called.\n- m_getstatus\n- m_null_inode\n- m_find_cbdata - ll_d_put\n- m_set_open_replay_data - ll_och_fill, ll_local_open\n- m_clear_open_replay_data - md_close\n- m_set_lock_data\n- m_lock_match\n- m_cancel_unused\n- m_renew_capa\n- m_unpack_capa\n- m_get_remote_perm\n- m_get_lustre_md\n- m_free_lustre_md\n- m_init_ea_size",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "bc5aa1a0c0b165e025142e79eb65b9a184028405",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
